# E2E cluster access: use the persistent tunnel (127.0.0.1:6445)

When inspecting the e2e nested cluster (kubectl, debugging a failed/hung run), reach the API server through the **user-maintained SSH tunnel** at `https://127.0.0.1:6445`.

- The auto-generated e2e kubeconfigs `/tmp/e2e/kubeconfig-<ip>.yml` point at a **transient** tunnel port (e.g. `127.0.0.1:54055`) that the test process opens. That tunnel **dies when the test process exits** (including on failure), so those kubeconfigs stop working right after a failing run.
- The user keeps a **separate, persistent** tunnel on `127.0.0.1:6445` that stays up after the test fails/hangs. Always prefer it for post-failure debugging.

## Use this kubeconfig

```bash
export KUBECONFIG=/tmp/e2e/kubeconfig-tunnel.yml
kubectl get ns
```

## (Re)generate it after a new run / cluster

The client certs rotate per cluster, and `/tmp/e2e/` may hold several `kubeconfig-<ip>.yml`. Pick the one whose creds actually authenticate against `:6445`, rewrite the server to the persistent port, and skip TLS verify (the cert SAN will not match `127.0.0.1`):

```bash
for src in $(ls -t /tmp/e2e/kubeconfig-*.yml | grep -v tunnel); do
  sed -E -e 's#server: https://127\.0\.0\.1:[0-9]+#server: https://127.0.0.1:6445#' \
         -e '/certificate-authority-data:/d' \
         -e 's#( *)server: https://127.0.0.1:6445#\1server: https://127.0.0.1:6445\n\1insecure-skip-tls-verify: true#' \
         "$src" > /tmp/e2e/kubeconfig-tunnel.yml
  KUBECONFIG=/tmp/e2e/kubeconfig-tunnel.yml kubectl get ns >/dev/null 2>&1 && break
done
export KUBECONFIG=/tmp/e2e/kubeconfig-tunnel.yml
```

Notes:
- `/tmp/e2e/kubeconfig-tunnel.yml` contains credentials — it lives only under `/tmp`, never commit it.
- This overrides the generic "standard kubeconfig location" note in `controller-redeploy-and-remote-e2e.mdc` for e2e cluster debugging.
